iPreparation		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBefore following steps in this post, you need to prepare:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- A laptop with the Optimus MUXed architecture. My laptop is a HP		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOMEN
17t-ck000 (i7-11800H, RTX 3070).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2022-01) My operating system is Arch Linux, with the latest		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iupdates.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2023-05) My operating system is now NixOS while writing this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iupdate. Most
of the steps, however, should still apply to other Linux		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idistros.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- It's recommended to turn off Secure Boot, but you likely did it		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ianyway
since you installed Linux. Theoretically, Secure Boot may cause		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilimitations
on the PCIe passthrough functionality.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Set up a virtual machine of Windows 10 or Windows 11 with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLibvirt
(Virt-Manager). I'm using Windows 11.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- My VM boots in UEFI (OVMF) mode, but theoretically, this guide will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ialso
work with BIOS (SeaBIOS) mode. There are no steps that		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ispecifically require
UEFI boot mode.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iYou MUST turn off Secure Boot in the VM! Or some drivers won't work!		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Windows 11 installer will check whether Secure Boot is enabled.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWith
Secure Boot off, the installer might prompt that the computer		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis
incompatible, and refuse to install Windows. You can follow the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isteps in
this post to fix the problem:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://www.tomshardware.com/how-to/bypass-windows-11-tpm-requirement	URL:https://www.tomshardware.com/how-to/bypass-windows-11-tpm-requirement	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Set up the emulated QXL graphics card first, so you get video output		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom
the VM.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (Optional) Depending on the video output ports on your computer,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipurchase an
HDMI, DP, or USB Type-C dummy plug. You can get one for a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifew bucks on
Amazon.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2023-05) Or you can choose to install a virtual monitor driver.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
IHDMI Dummy Plug	/usr/uploads/202201/hdmi-dummy-plug.jpg	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (Optional) A USB keyboard and mouse combo.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iA reminder before we begin:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Multiple reboots of the host OS is required, and your host OS may		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icrash! Back
up your data.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- You don't need to download any NVIDIA driver manually. Windows will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ido it for
you automatically.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If it doesn't, don't go any further than downloading the driver EXE		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand
double-clicking.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNever		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  specify the exact driver to be used in Device Manager.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Debugging will be harder if you do this.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPurchasing A New Optimus MUXed Laptop		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you are interested in GPU passthrough and are looking for a new		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilaptop, you
can refer to my guidelines.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe prerequisites for laptop GPU passthrough is:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The NVIDIA GPU itself must be capable of video output		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- There is at least one video output directly connected to that GPU		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, it's extremely rare for a laptop manufacturer to mention the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iport
connection schemes on their product pages, so we have to infer		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom more common
specifications:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Prefer a laptop with a MUX switch, aka ones that can switch their		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinternal
screen onto the dedicated GPU. In this case, the dedicated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU must be
capable of video output, and there's a high chance that		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe manufacturer
connected the chassis video outputs to the dedicated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Common examples are: 2020 and 2021 Lenovo Legion series, HP OMEN		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iseries,
and Dell G15.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI do not guarantee that this list is accurate!		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-  Do your own research or
ask a sales agent to make sure.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Or choose a laptop with a mid-range to high-end graphics card. For		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNVIDIA
GPUs the model number needs to end with 60 or larger.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- It's common for mid to top-tier NVIDIA GPUs to have video		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ioutput
functionality, and the manufacturer is likely to connect		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ichassis video
ports to them.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Do not purchase a laptop with a GPU that ends in 50 or lower, like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ian RTX
3050 or GTX 1650 Ti. They very likely don't support video		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ioutput.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Take advantage of unconditional return policies.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Since manufacturers won't advertise or won't even care much about		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itheir
video output connections, we have to guess from the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ispecifications and
advertising pages. Therefore, it's possible that		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyou followed every rule
above yet got a laptop that doesn't support		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU passthrough. In this case,
you may consider returning or reselling		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iit.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- In some countries, laptop manufacturers will only accept an		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iunconditional
return if the preinstalled Windows and Office are never		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iactivated online.
However, the latest Windows 11 requires you to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iactivate online in its
first-boot setup wizard. You may consider		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itrying GPU passthrough with a
Linux installation on your USB drive		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibefore activating Windows.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAbout Intel GVT-g Virtual GPUs		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i5th to 9th-Gen Intel integrated graphics support virtualizing the GPU		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iitself, or
in other words, splitting it into several virtual GPUs. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual GPUs can be
passed through into VMs so they get GPU		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iacceleration, while the host can still
display stuff on the very same		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, the GVT-g driver in Linux doesn't support 10th-Gen or newer		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIntel CPUs,
and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hIntel has no plan to support them	URL:https://github.com/intel/gvt-linux/issues/126	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i.
In addition, the GVT-g virtual GPU cannot form an Optimus		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration with an
NVIDIA GPU, so it isn't useful anyway.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThat's why we're ignoring GVT-g and focusing on the NVIDIA GPU in this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iguide.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(2023-05) About Intel SR-IOV Virtual GPUs		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i11th-Gen and later Intel integrated graphics support another form		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iof
virtualization: SR-IOV. Intel has		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hofficially released the source code to the kernel module with SR-IOV	URL:https://github.com/intel/linux-intel-lts/tree/lts-v5.15.49-adl-linux-220826T092047Z/drivers/gpu/drm/i915	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
but it isn't merged into Linux mainline as of now.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hThere's a third party project that ports the code into a DKMS module	URL:https://github.com/strongtz/i915-sriov-dkms	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
but success rate is not high according to reports in Issues section.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI tried it
with my i7-11800H and didn't succeed. Therefore, this time		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwe will not try
SR-IOV on Intel GPUs.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSteps		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iStop Host OS from Tampering with NVIDIA GPU		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> Most of the content is the same as		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1my post in 2021	/en/article/modify-computer/laptop-intel-nvidia-optimus-passthrough.lantian/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> .		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe NVIDIA driver on the Host OS will hold control of the dGPU, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istop VM from
using it. Therefore you need to replace the driver with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`vfio-pci`, built solely
for PCIe passthrough.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are the steps for disabling the NVIDIA driver and passing control		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito the
PCIe passthrough module:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Run `lspci -nn | grep NVIDIA` and obtain an output similar to:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Here `[10de:249d]` is the vendor ID and device ID of the dGPU, where		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`10de`
means this device is manufactured by NVIDIA, and `249d` means		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithis is a
RTX 3070. `228b` is the audio output on the HDMI port, which		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ishould also be
taken over by `vfio-pci`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create `/etc/modprobe.d/lantian.conf` with the following content:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- This configures `vfio-pci`, the kernel module responsible for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPCIe
passthrough, to manage the dGPU. `ids` is the vendor ID and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idevice ID of the
device to be passed through.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Modify `/etc/mkinitcpio.conf`, add the following contents to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`MODULES`:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- And remove anything related to NVIDIA drivers (such as `nvidia`), or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imake
sure they're listed after VFIO drivers. Now PCIe passthrough		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imodule will take
control of the dGPU in the early booting process,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipreventing NVIDIA drivers
from taking control.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Run `mkinitcpio -P` to update the initramfs.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Reboot.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(2023-05) If you're using NixOS, you can use the following config:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSetting up NVIDIA dGPU Passthrough		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1my post in 2021	/en/article/modify-computer/laptop-intel-nvidia-optimus-passthrough.lantian/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
I mentioned a lot of configurations to circumvent restrictions of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe NVIDIA
driver. But		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hsince version 465, NVIDIA lifted most of the restrictions	URL:https://nvidia.custhelp.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/5173	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
so theoretically, you pass a GPU into the VM, and everything should		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ijust work.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBut that's just the theory.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI still recommend everyone to follow all the steps and hide the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iVM
characteristics, because:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2022-01) Not all restructions are lifted for laptops.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt least in my tests, an incorrect PCIe bus address for the GPU and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
absence of a battery still causes passthrough to fail, and the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idriver will
error out with the infamous code 43.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2023-05) In the attempt today, the PCIe bus address and absence of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibattery
no longer affects outcome of GPU passthrough.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Even if NVIDIA driver isn't detecting VMs, the programs you run		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imight. Hiding
VM characteristics increases the chance to run them		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isuccessfully.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Examples include online games with anti-cheat systems, or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icommercial
software that require online activation.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd here we start:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Unlike the Optimus MUXless architecture, I didn't manually extract		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
graphic card's BIOS nor modify the UEFI firmware, and everything		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ijust works.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you cannot install the GPU driver after passing it into the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iVM,
including the cases that Windows won't automatically install them,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ior
NVIDIA's official installer errors out saying lack of compatible		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idevices,
you likely will still need to extract your GPU's video BIOS.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- To double-check, open Device Manager in the VM, and look at the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHardware
ID, which looks like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`PCI\VEN_10DE&DEV_1C8D&SUBSYS_39D117AA&REV_A1`. If
`SUBSYS` is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifollowed by a sequence of zeros, then the GPU video BIOS is
missing,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand you need the manual steps.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Refer to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1my post last year	/en/article/modify-computer/laptop-intel-nvidia-optimus-passthrough.lantian/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
specifically the NVIDIA GPU passthrough section, for detailed steps.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Modify your VM configuration, `virsh edit Windows`, and make the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifollowing
changes:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The ssdt1.dat is an ACPI table, and it emulates a fully-charged		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibattery. It
corresponds to the Base64 below. It can be converted to a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibinary file with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hBase64 decoding website	URL:https://base64.guru/converter/decode/file	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
1downloaded from this site	/usr/uploads/202007/ssdt1.dat	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i. Place it in the
root folder.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Modify permissions for the shared memory.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Modify `/etc/apparmor.d/local/abstractions/libvirt-qemu` and add		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithis
line:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then execute `sudo systemctl restart apparmor` to restart AppArmor.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create `/etc/tmpfiles.d/looking-glass.conf` with the following		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icontents,
replacing `lantian` to your username:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then execute
`sudo systemd-tmpfiles		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i/etc/tmpfiles.d/looking-glass.conf --create` to
make it effective.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Start the VM and wait a while. Windows will automatically install		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNVIDIA
drivers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If Device Manager shows the GPU with an exclamation sign and error		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icode 43,
you need to check if you've missed any steps and if you've		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconfigured
everything correctly.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2022-01)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSwitch Device Manager to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`Device by Connection`		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand verify
that the NVIDIA GPU is at Bus 1, Slot 0, Function 0. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iparent PCIe port
to the dGPU should be at Bus 0, Slot 1, Function 0.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIf they don't match, you need to reallocate PCIe addresses with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe
method above.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- (2023-05) This step is no longer needed in my attempt today.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If the OS didn't automatically install the NVIDIA driver, and your		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
imanually
downloaded driver installer also shows that the system is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iincompatible, you
need to check the properties of the GPU device.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iCheck if there is a
sequence of zeros after `SUBSYS` in its Hardware		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iID.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- If there is, refer to step 1.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
