iCutting Power to GPU When Unused		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2022-01-26 Update: testing shows that the NVIDIA GPU still isn't		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icompletely
shut down after applying the patch. The power draw is the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isame as before. This
section is now invalid.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> This section only applies to 20-series of NVIDIA GPUs or newer.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThey can shut
themselves down with the NVIDIA official drivers. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i10-series or older GPUs
don't support this feature.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> This section involves compiling a kernel yourself, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusing an patch
without extensive inspection or testing		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> . Not intended for novice users.
Evaluate the risks yourself.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen you aren't using the VM, the `vfio-pci` driver in charge of		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPCIe
passthrough sets the device to the `D3` mode, aka the power		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isaving mode of PCIe
devices. But there are two types of `D3` modes:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`D3hot`, where the device is
still powered, and `D3cold`, where the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idevice is shut off completely. Currently,
the `vfio-pci` driver in the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel only supports `D3hot`, and the NVIDIA GPU
will still consume		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iaround 10 watts of power since its chip power isn't cut. This
impacts		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe battery life of laptops.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAn NVIDIA engineer posted a patchset for `vfio-pci`'s `D3cold` support		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion the
Linux kernel mailing list. With this patchset, the NVIDIA GPU		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill be shut down
completely when the VM is off. It saves power for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iyour battery.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe patchset can be found at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20211115133640.2231-1-abhsahu@nvidia.com/T/	URL:https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20211115133640.2231-1-abhsahu@nvidia.com/T/	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i,
which consists of three patches. I combined the three patches and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iuploaded the
result to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/blob/master/linux-xanmod-lantian/0007-vfio-pci-d3cold.patch	URL:https://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/blob/master/linux-xanmod-lantian/0007-vfio-pci-d3cold.patch	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPatching kernel is relatively simple for Arch Linux. Most kernel		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPKGBUILDs in
AUR can apply patches automatically. All you have to do		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis to download the
PKGBUILD for a kernel and add the patch to its		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`source` section. See my commit
for an example:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
